      <hedline>
        <hl1>Faith in Global Warming</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Curt Gardner letter comments on Feb 11 John Tierney Op-Ed column about global warming</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>I can't argue with John Tierney on the religious aspect of environmentalism. But let's agree that there's another ''faith-based'' movement in America: belief in technology.</p>
        <p>Conceptual projects like ''geo-engineering schemes to cool the planet by blocking sunlight'' suggest an immense faith in the ability of humankind to engineer its way out of any problem that arises.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>I can't argue with John Tierney on the religious aspect of environmentalism. But let's agree that there's another ''faith-based'' movement in America: belief in technology.</p>
        <p>Conceptual projects like ''geo-engineering schemes to cool the planet by blocking sunlight'' suggest an immense faith in the ability of humankind to engineer its way out of any problem that arises.</p>
        <p>To entertain the thought of altering the planet's relationship with the sun, provider of the energy that creates and sustains life itself, is the thinking of a true believer.</p>
        <p>Curt Gardner  Portland, Ore., Feb. 11, 2006</p>
      </block>
